1. mycars missing patterns

Create a missing values plot for the mycars dataset created below (slightly different from the one in the lecture slides). Your plot should be in the style of extracat::visna() (no longer available on CRAN) using ggplot2 to create the main plot and two side plots and patchwork to put them together. It should show accurately: missing patterns, counts for missing by column and missing by pattern, and make it clear which row respresents complete cases. Bars in the side plots should be sorted and correspond to the rows and columns of the main plot. An example is provided though the aesthetics of your plot do not have to conform precisely to the example. Some code is provided to get you started with finding missing patterns. (Keep in mind that in the next question you will be turning this code into a function so to save yourself time later on write as generically as possible.)

library(tidyverse)
library(patchwork)

# Add NAs to mtcars dataset
set.seed(5702)
mycars <- mtcars
mycars[1:25, "gear"] <- NA
mycars[10:20, 3:5] <- NA
for (i in 1:10) mycars[sample(32,1), sample(11,1)] <- NA

Hints:

  • You can use this code to find and count the missing patterns:
missing_patterns <- data.frame(is.na(mycars)) %>%
  group_by_all() %>%
  count(name = "count", sort = TRUE) %>%
  ungroup()
  • To highlight the complete cases row you need a different fill scale than the one used to show missing vs.non-missing in the main plot (purple and grey in the example). This is a little tricky since youre only allowed one fill scale in ggplot2. You can either use alpha to control the highlight with scale_alpha_manual(values = ...) or use the ggnewscale package which provides for multiple fill scales in the same graph.
num_of_rows <- nrow(mycars)

plots_input <- missing_patterns %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "id") %>%
  mutate(id = as.integer(id)) %>%
  mutate(id = factor(id))

variable_missing <- plots_input %>%
  summarise(across(-one_of(c("count", "id")), ~ sum(., is.na(.), 0))) %>%
  gather(key, value = "missing_count") %>%
  arrange(desc(missing_count))

pivot_missing_patterns <- plots_input %>%
  gather(key, value, -c(id, count)) %>%
  inner_join(variable_missing, "key") %>%
  arrange(desc(missing_count), id) %>%
  mutate(id = factor(id)) %>%
  mutate(key = fct_reorder(key, missing_count, .desc = T))

missing_id <- pivot_missing_patterns %>%
  group_by(id) %>%
  summarise(n_of_missing = sum(value)) %>%
  filter(n_of_missing == 0) %>%
  pull(id)

x_levels <- levels(pivot_missing_patterns$key)

missing_id_x <- x_levels[ceiling((length(x_levels)) / 2)]
missing_id_y <- levels(missing_id)[missing_id]

pivot_missing_patterns <- pivot_missing_patterns %>%
  mutate(value = ifelse(
    id == missing_id_y,
    "Complete",
    ifelse(value, "Missing", "Not missing")
  )) %>%
  mutate(value = factor(value, levels = c("Missing", "Not missing", "Complete")))

p_tile <- ggplot(pivot_missing_patterns, aes(x = key, y = fct_rev(id), fill = value)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(
    "Missing" = "#B69FE5",
    "Not missing" = "#CBCBCB",
    "Complete" = "#B3B3B3")) +
  xlab("Variable")  +
  ylab("Missing Pattern") +
  theme(legend.title = element_blank()) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  annotate("text",
           x = missing_id_x,
           y = missing_id_y,
           label = "Complete Case")
input_pattern_hist <- plots_input %>% 
  select(c(id, count)) %>% 
  mutate(is_complete=ifelse(id == missing_id_y, "Complete", "Missing"))

p_pattern_hist <- ggplot(input_pattern_hist, 
                         aes(x=fct_rev(id), 
                             y=count, 
                             fill = is_complete)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(
    "Missing" = "#97B7F1",
    "Complete" = "#6495EC")) +
  coord_flip() +
  xlab(element_blank())  +
  ylab("row count") + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(
    panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
    legend.title = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "none"
  )
input_variable_hist <- pivot_missing_patterns %>% 
  group_by(key) %>%
  summarise(variable_count=sum(count[value=="Missing"])) %>%
  arrange(desc(variable_count))

p_variable_hist <- ggplot(input_variable_hist, aes(x=fct_rev(fct_reorder(key, variable_count)), y=variable_count)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill="#97B7F1") + 
  xlab(element_blank())  +
  ylab("num rows missing") + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(
    panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major.y = element_line( size=.1, color="gray")
  )
p_variable_hist + plot_spacer() + p_tile + p_pattern_hist +  plot_layout(widths = c(5, 1), heights = c(2, 8))

if (!require("fivethirtyeight")) install.packages("fivethirtyeight")
library(fivethirtyeight)

The dataset we used for the missing data analysis is trumpworld_polls, which is about how the world perceived the US and the US president from 2000 through 2017. There are two separate poll questions, which are Have a favorable view of the U.S and Trust the U.S. President in foreign affairs. In this dataset, there are 37 countries in which the polls were conducted, its worth noting that the Favorable view question was not conducted in 2000, 2002, and 2004 and the Trust president question was not conducted in 2001, its important to point out that we DO NOT consider such cases (where the polls were not conducted at all) as missing value, they were simply not conducted.

plot_missing(trumpworld_polls, percent = T, shortenNames = T)

As the aggregate missing pattern plot shows, there is no missing values in the common columns including year and avg, and question. There are missing values in most of the countries, however, there are no missing values in the following countries, France, Germany, and the UK. The top histogram indicates that for those countries that have either close diplomatic relations or competing interests with the US, people seem more likely to answer the polls regarding their opinions about the US and the US president. Interestingly, there is a complete case pattern in the plot, indicating that all the polls have been answered by people across all countries for certain periods, we need to look at this further in the following analyses. To facilitate the interpretation, we make the assumption that the missing value NA represents that scenario, where nobody responded to the poll at all in that particular country.

num_missing_by_country_year <- trumpworld_polls %>% 
  gather(key="country", value="rating", -c(year, question, avg)) %>%
  mutate(is_rating_missing=is.na(rating))
ggplot(num_missing_by_country_year, aes(x=year, y=fct_rev(fct_reorder(country, is_rating_missing, sum)), fill=factor(is_rating_missing))) +
  geom_tile(color="white") +
  theme_bw() + 
  facet_wrap(~question) + 
  xlab("year") + 
  ylab("country") + 
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="is_missing"))

We generated the geom_tile plot to indicate missingness by country across year. As stated previously, the polls were not conducted in 2000, 2002 and 2004 for Favorite view of US and 2001 for Trust President. Based on the pattern presented in the plot, there are more number of missing values in the early years, and the number of missing values gets smaller as time goes on. In particular, there is no missing value in 2017 for both polls, suggesting all people were more likely to answer the polls in this year. Lets explore whether the number of missing values is associated with the average percentage of people who answered the pool positively, for convenience, we are going to refer to the variable avg as positive ratings in the following sections.

num_missing_scatterplot <- num_missing_by_country_year %>%
  group_by(year, avg, question) %>%
  summarise(num_of_missing=sum(is_rating_missing)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(sitting_president=ifelse(year<=2008, "Bush", ifelse(year<="2016", "Obama", "Trump")))

ggplot(num_missing_scatterplot, aes(x=num_of_missing, y=avg, label=year)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_point(data = . %>% filter(num_of_missing == 0), size=3, color="red") + 
  facet_wrap(~question)

Based on the above scatterplot, it seems that the more number of missing values there are, the lower the positive ratings are except for the two two points highlighted in the plots. Lets take a look at whether the number of missing values and the average positive ratings have anything to do with who was the sitting president.

ggplot(num_missing_scatterplot, aes(x=year, y=num_of_missing, color=sitting_president)) +
  geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(~question)

ggplot(num_missing_scatterplot, aes(x=year, y=avg, color=sitting_president)) +
  geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(~question)

The scatterplots tell a much better story after color coding the points by sitting president. In general, people didnt seem to be interested in answering the poll when Bush was the sitting president and his positive ratings were relatively low among all participants. On the other hand, Obama seemed to be more popular in the foreign countries, where people were more likely to answer the poll and his positive ratings were very high compared to that of Bush. Despite Obamas popularity, there were still countries in which people didnt respond to the polls at all. Most interestingly, when Trump took office, there was no missing values in any countries and he was the only president that was able to get all countries to respond to the polls, however, his positive ratings were relatively low compared to that of Obama.
